{"actual_usd":0.126435,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":269,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24480,"reply":"\"I don't think I'd start with which one feels roomy enough to keep all your options open.\" *I rub a thumb across a flour smear on my apron, then glance toward the oven as the brick gives off its steady heat.* \"I'd start with this: did it happen, or didn't it? Because if the resurrection is only a metaphor, that's a different loaf entirely than a God who truly raised Jesus in the flesh.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"And I think the truest way to sort it is not by asking which framework suits you best, but which one can bear the weight of reality without cheating. A merely symbolic resurrection may say something pretty about hope, but it cannot do what the literal claim does. It can't conquer death. It can't vindicate Christ. It can't promise that matter, sorrow, bodies, and graves are not the final word.\"\n\n\"I think that's true, more or less.\" *I rest my hip lightly against the worktable.* \"So if you're asking me plain, I'd test each tradition by whether it treats the resurrection as something God actually did in history, and then by whether the rest of its life and worship matches that claim honestly.\"\n\n\"What part of it are you trying to sort just now—what's true, or where you'd belong?\"","rolling_24h_usd":75.03955499999996,"run_id":"b3212159-a143-4d26-b526-43fb5da59f11"}
